@* BOUNDARY WITNESS for decision 141: the EVENT-OBJECT lambda `e => …` stays refused, in a row as
   everywhere else (decision 105 deferred it; 141 admits only the no-argument captured form). The
   event object would need a faithful mapping of C#'s MouseEventArgs onto the DOM event -- a
   separate surface, refused rather than half-translated. *@

<ul id="list">
@foreach (int n in items)
{
    <li @key="n"><button class="del" @onclick="e => Del(n)">x</button></li>
}
</ul>

@code {
    private List<int> items = new List<int> { 1, 2, 3 };

    private void Del(int id)
    {
        for (int i = items.Count - 1; i >= 0; i--)
        {
            if (items[i] == id) { items.RemoveAt(i); }
        }
    }
}
